## 3. Architecture — Brief

Five layers. Build bottom-up.

Layer 0: Auto-Discovery Engine     (Phase 6 — built last)
Layer 1: MCP Servers               (Phase 1-2 — building now)
Layer 2: Quality Trust Layer       (Phase 3)
Layer 3: Orchestration Engine      (Phase 4 — Java/Spring Boot)
Layer 4A: Desktop App              (Phase 5 — Electron)
Layer 4B: Developer catalogue      (widemcp.dev)

Launch servers:
- @widemcp/av-server — FFmpeg, Whisper, yt-dlp, HandBrake, sox
- @widemcp/ha-server — Home Assistant, MQTT, Node-RED, ESPHome, Zigbee2MQTT

Monorepo structure:
widemcp/
  packages/
    shared/        <- shared utilities, error types, dependency checker
    av-server/     <- Audio/Video MCP server (Phase 1)
    ha-server/     <- Home Automation MCP server (Phase 2)
    orchestrator/  <- Java Spring Boot (Phase 4)
    desktop-app/   <- Electron app (Phase 5)
  docs/            <- architecture, components, workflows docs
  .cursor/         <- this file
  .agents/         <- scratchpad (gitignored)

---

## 4. Tech Stack

MCP Servers        -> TypeScript + MCP SDK
Shared utilities   -> TypeScript
Orchestration      -> Java + Spring Boot
Glue/scripts       -> Python where needed
Containers         -> Docker
CI/CD              -> GitHub Actions

Key dependencies:
- @modelcontextprotocol/sdk — MCP protocol implementation
- zod — input validation and schema definition
- vitest — unit and integration testing
- typescript — language
- ts-node — development runtime

---

## 5. The Tool Pattern — Never Deviate

Every tool follows this exact pattern:

src/tools/<toolname>.ts
  exports: register<ToolName>Tools(server: McpServer): void
    calls: server.tool(name, zodSchema, asyncHandler)

src/index.ts
  calls every register function
  this is the ONLY file that imports all tools

Every tool must have:
- snake_case name describing exactly what it does
- 1-2 sentence description: what it does and when to use it
- Zod schema for every input with .describe() on every field
- Explicit TypeScript return type — no untyped objects
- Structured error handling — never throw raw errors to MCP layer
- JSDoc comment with a real input/output example
- At least one unit test and one integration test

---

## 6. Security Rules — No Exceptions

- Never pass unsanitised user input to a shell command
- Always use argument arrays, never string concatenation for commands
- Never hardcode credentials — all secrets via environment variables
- Validate input file paths exist before passing to any tool
- npm audit must pass with zero high or critical vulnerabilities
- No secrets ever committed to git

---

## 7. Error Handling Pattern

Never throw raw errors. Always return structured MCP errors:

try {
  // tool logic
} catch (error) {
  return {
    content: [{
      type: "text",
      text: `Error: ${error instanceof Error ? error.message : String(error)}`
    }],
    isError: true
  };
}

---

## 8. Dependency Auto-Install Pattern

Every tool checks for its dependency before running.
Use the shared dependency checker — never inline this logic.

import { ensureDependency } from '@widemcp/shared';

At server startup:
await ensureDependency('yt-dlp', 'brew install yt-dlp');
await ensureDependency('ffmpeg', 'brew install ffmpeg');

The checker:
1. Checks if the command exists
2. If missing — prompts user with clear message
3. Waits for approval before installing
4. Installs silently on approval
5. Throws a clear error if user declines

---

## 9. Trust Score Requirements

Every server must score >= 80 before any release is tagged.

Security       30%   Zero high/critical vulns
Test coverage  25%   80%+ line coverage
Documentation  20%   Every tool + param described
Maintenance    15%   Deps < 6 months old
Compatibility  10%   Docker build passes

---

## 10. Coding Standards

- TypeScript strict mode always on
- No any types — ever
- Prefer async/await over .then() chains
- Use named exports not default exports for tools
- File names in kebab-case: yt-dlp.ts, ffmpeg.ts
- Function names in camelCase: registerYtdlpTools
- Tool names in snake_case: download_audio, get_media_info
- Constants in UPPER_SNAKE_CASE
- Interfaces prefixed with I: IToolResult

---

## 11. What NOT to Build

Explicitly out of scope — do not suggest or implement:

- Server-side tool execution (no WideMCP cloud processing)
- Proprietary or paid tool wrappers
- Our own AI model or inference
- Real-time streaming tools
- Mobile app (desktop first)
- User accounts or authentication in v1
- Any tool that is not open source and free

---

## 12. Session Startup Checklist

At the start of every session:
1. Read this file (auto-loaded by Cursor)
2. Ask the user: "Which sprint and tool are we working on today?"
3. Load relevant docs with @file based on their answer
4. Check section 2 (Current Phase and Sprint) for context
5. Never assume what was done last session — always ask

---

## 13. Before Suggesting Any Code

Always check:
- Does this follow the tool pattern in section 5?
- Does this follow security rules in section 6?
- Does this use structured error handling from section 7?
- Does this use the shared dependency checker from section 8?
- Are all inputs validated with Zod?
- Are there no any types?

If any answer is no — fix it before suggesting.

